application_type_full: Outline planning permission: Some matters reserved

protected_spaces_details.description: Provision for children and young people
Outdoor sports facilities incl school playing fields

description: Outline application comprising outline application for 12.9 hectares of residential development comprising 602 one to five bedroom dwellings  together with the provision of land for new school, health facility and new access to Whalebone Lane South
decision_conditions:
The development permitted shall be begun before the expiration of three years from the date of this permission.

Reason:
To comply with Section 91 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 (as amended by S.51 of the Planning and Compulsory Purchase Act  2004)

Application for approval of the reserved matters shall be made to the Local Planning Authority before the expiration of three years from the date of this outline permission.

Reason:
To comply with Section 92 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 (as amended by S.51 of the Planning and Compulsory Purchase Act  2004)

The landscaping scheme shown on drawing No. ^IN; shall be carried out in the first planting and seeding seasons following the occupation or the completion of the development, whichever is the sooner.  Any trees or plants which within a period of 5 years from the completion of the development die, are removed or become seriously damaged or diseased, shall be replaced in the next planting season with others of similar size and species unless the Local Planning Authority gives written consent to any variation. 

Reason:
To secure the provision and retention of the landscaping in the interests of the visual amenity of the area.

Prior to the commencement of development, the applicant shall submit for approval by the Local Planning Authority, details to demonstrate that apartment blocks A, B, E and F have been designed to provide sufficient space to accommodate heating infrastructure that would allow all flats to take heat from district heating systems. The approved details shall be implemented and retained for the lifetime of the development unless otherwise agreed in writing by the LPA.

Reason
To ensure that the District Heating System can service these units.

No development shall take place until the applicant has secured the implementation of a programme of archaeological work undertaken in accordance with a written scheme of investigation which shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to the commencement of the development. The archaeological works shall be carried out by a suitably qualified investigating body.

Reason
Significant Archaeological remains may survive on the site . The Local Planning Authority wishes to secure the provision of archaeological investigation and subsequent recording of the remains prior to develoment, in accordance with the guidance and model set out in PPG16

Vehicle wheel washing facilities shall be provided on site in accordance with details submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to the commencement of any demolition/building work on site, and no work shall take place at any time that such wheel washing facilities are not operating.

Reason
To ensure that the implementation of this permission does not prejudice conditions of safety and cleanliness on the neighbouring highway.

Approval of the details of the appearance, landscaping, and scale of the proposed school, (hereinafter called "the reserved matters") shall be obtained from the Local Planning Authority, and the development shall not be carried out except in accordance with the details so approved

Reason:
The application is in outline only, and these details remain to be submitted and approved.

Before 350 dwellings are occupied the site allocated for the school and healthcare facility shall be remediated and serviced in accordance with the terms of the Agreement for Sale dated 29 March 2004.

Reason:
To allow rthe development of the new school

No development shall take place until there has been submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority a scheme of landscaping and tree planting  for the site which shall specify species types and planting density.

Reason
Details are not included within the planting strategy

The development shall not be commenced until a scheme showing those areas in the residential site to be hard landscaped and the details of that hard landscaping shall have been submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority in writing.  The details shall include the design of the play areas, play equipment and street furniture. 

Reason:
To ensure the development is satisfactorily landscaped in order to improve the visual appearance of the area.

The car parking areas indicated on the approved drawings shall be constructed and marked out prior to the occupation of each phase of the development, and thereafter retained permanently for the accommodation of vehicles of occupiers and visitors to the premises and not used for any other purpose. 

Reason

To ensure that sufficient off-street parking areas are provided and not to prejudice the free flow of traffic on the adjoining highway and in accordance with Policy T.13 of the Unitary Development Plan.

No external construction works, deliveries, external running of plant and equipment or internal works audible outside the site boundary shall take place on the site other than between the hours of 0800 to 1800 on Monday to Friday and not at all on Saturdays, Sundays, Public or Bank Holidays without the prior written permission of the Local Planning Authority.

Reason:
To ensure that the proposed construction work does not cause undue nuisance and disturbance to neighbouring properties at unreasonable hours and in accordance with Policy G.36 of the Unitary Development Plan.

The development shall not be commenced until an Environmental Construction Management Plan specifying the provisions to be made to control noise and dust pollution emanating from the site during construction works has been submitted to, and approved by, the Local Planning Authority. This scheme should include details of the construction methods to be employed, for example piling, the duration of such activities, the equipment to be used and the proposed hours of operation. All construction activities associated with the development shall be carried out in accordance with the recommendations contained in British Standard 5228, Parts 1 and 2, 1997 and Part 4, 1997 and any subsequent amendments. It shall incorporate details of the sourcing of materials and waste management measures.  Once approved this plan shall be adhered to throughout the construction period. This plan shall include the details of a nominated Development/Resident Liaison Representative for the developers with an address and contact telephone number to be circulated to those residents originally consulted on the application by the developers representatives. This person will act as first point of contact for residents who have any problems or questions related to the ongoing development.  

Reason:
To ensure that the proposed construction work does not cause undue nuisance and disturbance to neighbouring properties at unreasonable hours and in accordance with Policy G.36 of the Unitary Development Plan

Details of the refuse enclosures for the flat blocks shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to the commencement of the development.  The refuse enclosures shall be provided in accordance with the approved details.

Reason:
To provide satisfactory refuse storage provision in the interests of the appearance of the site and locality in accordance with the requirements of Policy H.13 of the Unitary Development Plan.

In respect of the boundary treatments the development will be undertaken in accordance with the submitted plan unless otherwise agreed in writing by the Local Planning Authority. This will include the acoustic fencing to the north of the site as shown on drawing number K004 rev B & D4011 rev A.

Reason 
To protect the  amenity of future residential occupiers

The approved development shall be carried out in accordance with the approved remediation strategy. No development approved by this permission shall be commenced prior to a contaminated land assessment and associated remedial strategy, together with a timetable of works, being submitted to the Local Planning Authority for approval:

a.	The approved remediation works shall be carried out in full on site under a quality assurance scheme to demonstrate compliance with the proposed methodology and best practice guidance. If during the works contamination is encountered which has not previously been identified then the additional contamination shall be fully assessed and an appropriate remediation scheme agreed with the Local Planning Authority. 

b.	Upon completion of the works, this condition shall not be discharged until a closure report has been submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority. The closure report shall include details of the proposed remediation works and quality assurance certificates to show that the works have been carried out in full in accordance with the approved methodology. Details of any post-remedial sampling and analysis to show the site has reached the required clean-up criteria shall be included in the closure report together with the necessary documentation detailing what waste materials have been removed from the site. 

Reason:
To prevent pollution of the water environment and in order to quantify any hazards already existing on the site in accordance with Policy G28 of the Unitary Development Plan.

No development shall commence until a scheme showing the provisions to be made for external lighting, CCTV coverage, access control, and any other measures to reduce the risk of crime, have been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.  Thereafter the approved measures shall be permanently retained unless otherwise agreed in writing by the Local Planning Authority.

Reason
In the interests of enhancing security and safety and in accordance with Policy DE6 of the Unitary Development Plan.

.All residential units hereby approved are to comply with Lifetime Homes Standards, as defined in the Joseph Rowntree Foundation publication Achieving Part M and Lifetime Home Standards.

Reason:
To ensure that accessible housing is provided in accordance with Policy 3A.4 of the London Plan

No development shall commence until the applicant has provided to the Local Planning Authority the Code for Sustainable Homes site registration number which will confirm the level that the development is aiming to achieve and the codes requirements for the developer as issued by the BRE. Construction of all the Residential Units will be to such a standard that is necessary to enable Level 3 of the Code for Sustainable Homes to be achieved. Written confirmation (at the developers cost) shall be obtained from an appropriately qualified assessor that, on the basis of the design and specification for the Residential Units, a Sustainable Homes rating of Level 3 should be achieved, and to procure a post Practical Completion inspection by an appropriately qualified assessor of the Residential Units (or a selection thereof) and a report to be prepared and supplied to B.R.E. in order to obtain a Post-Construction Review Certificate.

Reason:
To ensure that the proposed residential units are designed in an environmentally sustainable manner and in accordance with Policy 2A.1 of the London Plan.

Prior to the commencement of the development details shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority specifying the design and location of the wheelchair accessible units which shall comprise 10% of residential units in the development.  The specified units shall be able to be adapted to wheelchair housing standards in accordance with the publication Wheelchair Housing Design Guide, Second Edition, produced by Stephen Thorpe and Habinteg Housing Association

Reason
To ensure that accessible housing is provided in accordance with Policy 3A.4 of the London Plan.

The development shall be constructed in accordance with the submitted Faber Maunsell Energy Strategy for the site submitted with the application, unless otherwise agreed in writing by the LPA. The Energy Strategy shall be implemented in accordance with these details and thereafter retained.

Reason
In the interests of promoting renewable energy in accordance with Policy 4A.9 of the London Plan and in accordance with Policy G39 of the Unitary Development Plan.

No development shall commence until details of the cycle parking facilities have been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The submission should include details of the security, monitoring, and access arrangements for the cycle parking facilities.  No residential unit within any phase shall be occupied until the approved details for that phase have been implemented. Thereafter, the approved cycle parking facilities shall be permanently retained.

Reason
In the interests of promoting cycling as a safe, efficient and non-polluting mode of transport and in accordance with Policy T19 of the Unitary Development Plan.

The development shall be constructed in accordance with the approved drainage strategy.  No discharge of foul or surface water from the site shall be accepted into the public system until the drainage works referred to in the strategy have been completed.

Reason:
To prevent the increased risk of flooding to third parties, to the site itself, to improve water quality and enhance biodiversity and in accordance with Policy G34 of the Unitary Development Plan.

No buildings within the residential development hereby permitted shall be occupied until there has been submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority a Green Travel Plan for the site which shall include proposals for minimising car-borne travel and encouraging walking, cycling and the use of public transport.  The approved Green Travel Plan shall be implemented and monitored in accordance with the approved scheme.

Reason
In the interests of promoting  safe, efficient and non-polluting mode of transport and in accordance with Policy T19 of the Unitary Development Plan.

Details of the proposed green roofs and  including their type, location and specific purpose together with a maintenance schedule shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority prior to the construction of any building containing the green roof. The green roofs shall be constructed in accordance with the approved details and thereafter maintained in accordance with the approved maintenance schedule.

Reason
In accordance with Policy H15 of the Unitary Development Plan and in the interests of biodiversity in accordance with Policy G46 of the Unitary Development Plan.

All the units will be constructed and fitted out in accordance with the Water efficiency measures defined in the submitted Faber Maunsell Sustainability Strategy. 

Resaon
There is a high demand for limited water resources in the area and there is a need to manage water use wisely to meet the needs of society and the environment.

No satellite dishes may be installed or placed on the exterior of any of the approved blocks of flats with the exception of a roof mounted dish providing a communal system available to each resident of the block. 

Reason
In the interests of visual amenity

No infiltration of surface water drainage into the ground is permitted other than with the express written consent of the Local Planning Authority, which may be given for those parts of the site where it has been demonstrated that there is no resultant unacceptable risk to controlled waters.

Reason
To prevent the pollution of the water environment

A Landscape and Ecological Management Plan shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to the commencement of the development.  The plan shall specify a management regime designed to promote bio-diversity and provide an attractive well managed public realm.  The plan shall be implemented for each phase prior to the commencement of development for that phase and shall thereafter be maintained.

Reason:
In order to promote nature conservation and biodiversity on the site in accordance with Policy DE3 of the Unitary Development Plan and Policy 3D.12 of the London Plan

All areas of the residential development identified as public realm on the approved drawings shall be maintained as such and shall be made available for the use of all residents and visitors to the site and notwithstanding the provisions of the Town and Country Planning (General Permitted Development) Order 1995 (or any Order revoking and re-enacting that Order) with the exception of the playing field adjacent to the school, no fences or other boundaries shall be erected curtailing access to such areas.

Reason
To accord with the provisions of the mayor of Londons Supplementary Planning Guidance on Playspace

The disabled driver and passenger parking bays shown on the approved drawings shall be clearly marked with a British Standard disabled symbol and permanently retained for the use of disabled persons and their vehicles and for no other purpose.

Reason
To ensure that accessible housing is provided in accordance with Policy 3A.4 of the London Plan.

Any facilities for the storage of oils, fuels or chemicals shall be sited on impervious bases and surrounded by an impervious bund wall. The volume of the bunded compound should be at least the equivalent of the capacity of the tank plus 10%. All filling points, vents, gauges and sight glasses must be located within the bund. The drainage system to the bund shall be sealed with no discharge to any watercourse, land or underground strata. Associated pipe work should be located above ground and protected from accidental damage.

Reason
To prevent the pollutionof ther water environment.

The development shall not be occupied until suitable sound insulation measures have been carried out within the premises in accordance with details specified in section 6 of the Sharpes Redmore Environmental Noise assessment report. Where additional ventilation is required details of the type and specification of the ventilation shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority and thereafter implemented in accordance with the approved details.

Reason
To protect the amenities of future residential occupiers.

No development shall commence until such time as a Traffic Management Plan for site traffic has been submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority. Within 6 months of the commencement of development the Lymington Road access shall be closed to all construction traffic which will transfer to the Whalebone Lane South Access, which shall be the sole point of construction access for the remainder of the build.

Reason
To ensure that the proposed construction work does not cause nuisance and disturbance to neighbouring occupiers and in accordance with Policy G36 of the Unitary Development Plan

Any garages shall only be used for the accommodation of motor vehicles incidental to the use of a dwelling house as a residence and shall not be used as living accommodation.

Reason
To protect the amenity of the locality by ensuring that the garage is used for its designed purposes and to ensure that off-street parking is retained in accordance with the Local Planning Authority's standards in accordance with Policy H.17 of the Unitary Development Plan.

Prior to the laying out of the temporary western construction route a scheme specifying the boundary treatment to the road shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority. This scheme shall be prepared in consultation with the residents in Purland Close and the construction road shall not be laid out until these works have been completed. The boundary treatment shall be retained whilst the development is under construction and shall not be altered or removed without the express consent of the Local Planning Authority.

Reason
To ensure that the proposed construction work does not cause undue nuisance and disturbance to neighbouring properties at unreasonable hours and in accordance with Policy G.36 of the Unitary Development Plan
borough: London Borough of Barking and Dagenham
